1 license at a time. The procedures for such designation may be further defined by
2 compact commission rule.
3 B. Nothing in this section shall require that the state of qualifying licensure be
4 the state of primary residence or state of primary practice for the licensee.
5 C. Nothing in this compact shall interfere with a licensee’s ability to hold a
6 single state license in multiple states.
7 D. Nothing in this compact shall affect the requirements established by a
8 member state for the issuance of a single state license.
9 SECTION 6. ACTIVE MILITARY MEMBER OR THEIR SPOUSES
10 An active military member or their spouse shall not be required to pay a fee to the
11 commission for a compact privilege. If a member state chooses to charge a member
12 state fee, it may choose to charge a reduced fee or no fee to an active military member
13 or their spouse for a compact privilege.
14 SECTION 7. ADVERSE ACTIONS
15 A. A member state in which a licensee is issued a compact qualifying license
16 shall have the exclusive authority to impose adverse action against the compact
17 qualifying license issued by that member state.
18 B. A member state may take adverse action based on current significant
19 investigative information of a remote state, so long as the member state follows its own
20 procedures for imposing adverse action.
21 C. Nothing in this compact shall override a member state’s decision that
22 participation in an alternative program may be used in lieu of adverse action and that
23 such participation shall remain non-public if required by the member state’s laws or
24 rules.
25 D. A remote state shall have the authority to:
26 1. Take adverse actions as set forth herein against a licensee’s compact
27 privilege in that state; and
Page 11 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 2. Issue subpoenas for both hearings and investigations that require the
2 attendance and testimony of witnesses as well as the production of evidence.
3 a. Subpoenas may be issued by a member state athletic training licensing
4 authority for the attendance and testimony of witnesses and the production of evidence.
5 b. A member state which issues a subpoena may request service of that
6 subpoena by another member state. The member state receiving the request to serve a
7 subpoena shall serve the subpoena if it is deemed enforceable by a court of competent
8 jurisdiction according to the practice and procedure in the receiving member state.
9 c. The issuing authority shall pay any witness fees, travel expenses, mileage,
10 and other fees required by the service statutes of the state where the witnesses or
11 evidence are located.
12 E. For purposes of taking adverse action, a member state shall give the same
13 priority and effect to reported conduct received from another member state as it would
14 if the conduct had occurred within that state. In so doing, the investigating member
15 state shall apply its own state laws to determine appropriate action.
16 F. A member state, if otherwise permitted by state law, may recover from the
17 affected licensee the costs of investigations and dispositions of cases resulting from any
18 adverse action taken against that licensee.
19 G. Joint Investigations:
20 1. In addition to the authority granted to a member state by its respective state
21 law, any member state may participate with other member states in joint investigations
22 of licensees.
23 2. Member states shall share any current significant investigative information,
24 litigation, or compliance materials in furtherance of any joint or individual
25 investigation initiated under the compact. In sharing such information between
26 member state athletic trainer licensing authorities, all information obtained shall be
27 kept confidential, except as otherwise mutually agreed upon by the sharing and
