2 l. Other matters as specified in rules of the compact commission.
3 5. If a meeting, or portion of a meeting, is closed, the compact commission’s
4 legal counsel or designee shall certify that the meeting will be closed and reference
5 each relevant exempting provision, and such reference shall be recorded in the
6 minutes. All minutes and documents of a closed meeting shall remain under seal,
7 subject to release only by a majority vote of the compact commission or order of a court
8 of competent jurisdiction.
9 G. Financing of the Compact Commission:
10 1. The compact commission shall pay, or provide for the payment of, the
11 reasonable expenses of its establishment, organization, and ongoing activities.
12 2. The compact commission may accept any and all appropriate revenue
13 sources as provided in this section.
14 3. The compact commission may levy on and collect an annual assessment
15 from each member state and impose fees on licensees of member states to whom it
16 grants a compact privilege to cover the cost of the operations and activities of the
17 compact commission and its staff, which must be in a total amount sufficient to cover
18 its annual budget as approved each year for which revenue is not provided by other
19 sources. The aggregate annual assessment amount for member states shall be allocated
20 based upon a formula that the compact commission shall promulgate by rule.
21 4. The compact commission shall not incur obligations of any kind prior to
22 securing the funds or a loan adequate to meet the same; nor shall the compact
23 commission pledge the credit of any of the member states, except by and with the
24 authority of the member state.
25 5. The compact commission shall keep accurate accounts of all receipts and
26 disbursements. The receipts and disbursements of the compact commission shall be
27 subject to the financial review or audit and accounting procedures established under
Page 19 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 its bylaws. However, all receipts and disbursements of funds handled by the compact
2 commission shall be subject to an annual financial review or audit by a certified or
3 licensed public accountant, and the report of the financial review or audit shall be
4 included in and become part of the annual report of the compact commission.
5 H. Qualified Immunity, Defense, and Indemnification:
6 1. The members, officers, executive director, employees and representatives of
7 the compact commission shall be immune from suit and liability, both personally and
8 in their official capacity, for any claim for damage to or loss of property or personal
9 injury or other civil liability caused by or arising out of any actual or alleged act, error,
10 or omission that occurred, or that the person against whom the claim is made had a
11 reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope of compact commission
12 employment, duties or responsibilities; provided that nothing in this paragraph shall be
13 construed to protect any such person from suit or liability for any damage, loss, injury,
14 or liability caused by the intentional or willful or wanton misconduct of that person.
15 The procurement of insurance of any type by the compact commission shall not in any
16 way compromise or limit the immunity granted hereunder.
17 2. The compact commission shall defend any member, officer, executive
18 director, employee, and representative of the compact commission in any civil action
19 seeking to impose liability arising out of any actual or alleged act, error, or omission
20 that occurred within the scope of compact commission employment, duties, or
21 responsibilities, or as determined by the compact commission that the person against
22 whom the claim is made had a reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope
23 of compact commission employment, duties, or responsibilities; provided that nothing
24 herein shall be construed to prohibit that person from retaining their own counsel at
25 their own expense; and provided further, that the actual or alleged act, error, or
26 omission did not result from that person’s intentional or willful or wanton misconduct.
27 3. The compact commission shall indemnify and hold harmless any member,
Page 20 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 officer, executive director, employee, and representative of the compact commission for
2 the amount of any settlement or judgment obtained against that person arising out of
3 any actual or alleged act, error, or omission that occurred within the scope of compact
4 commission employment, duties, or responsibilities, or that such person had a
5 reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope of compact commission
6 employment, duties, or responsibilities, provided that the actual or alleged act, error, or
7 omission did not result from the intentional or willful or wanton misconduct of that
8 person.
9 4. Nothing herein shall be construed as a limitation on the liability of any
10 licensee for professional malpractice or misconduct, which shall be governed solely by
11 any other applicable state laws.
12 5. Nothing in this compact shall be interpreted to waive or otherwise abrogate
13 a member state’s state action immunity or state action affirmative defense with respect
14 to antitrust claims under the Sherman Act, Clayton Act, or any other state or federal
15 antitrust or anticompetitive law or regulation.
16 6. Nothing in this compact shall be construed to be a waiver of sovereign
17 immunity by the member states or by the compact commission.
18 SECTION 9. DATA SYSTEM
19 A. The commission shall provide for the development, maintenance, operation,
20 and utilization of a coordinated data system and reporting system containing licensure,
21 compact privileges, adverse action, and the presence of current significant investigative
22 information on all licensees and applicants for a license in member states.
23 B. Notwithstanding any other provision of state law to the contrary, a member
24 state shall submit a uniform data set to the data system on all licensees, applicants, and
25 others to whom this compact is applicable as required by the rules of the compact
26 commission, including:
27 1. Personally identifying information;
Page 21 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 2. Licensure data;
2 3. Adverse actions against a licensee, license applicant or compact privilege
3 and information related thereto;
4 4. Non-confidential information related to alternative program participation,
5 the beginning and ending dates of such participation, and other information related to
6 such participation;
7 5. Any denial of an application for licensure, and the reason(s) for such
8 denial, (excluding the reporting of any criminal history record information where
9 prohibited by law);
10 6. A binary determination regarding the presence of current significant
11 investigative information; and
12 7. Other information that may facilitate the administration of this compact or
13 the protection of the public, as determined by the rules of the commission.
14 C. The records and information provided to a member state pursuant to this
15 compact or through the data system, when certified by the commission or an agent
16 thereof, shall constitute the authenticated business records of the commission, and
17 shall be entitled to any associated hearsay exception in any relevant judicial, quasi-
18 judicial or administrative proceedings in a member state.
19 D. Current significant investigative information pertaining to a licensee in any
20 member state will only be available to other member states.
21 E. It is the responsibility of the member states to monitor the data system to
22 determine whether adverse action has been taken against a licensee or license
23 applicant. Adverse action information pertaining to a licensee or license applicant in
24 any member state will be available to any other member state.
25 F. Member states contributing information to the data system may designate
26 information that may not be shared with the public without the express permission of
27 the contributing state.
Page 22 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 G. Any information submitted to the data system that is subsequently expunged
2 pursuant to federal law or the laws of the member state contributing the information
3 shall be removed from the data system.
4 SECTION 10. RULEMAKING
5 A. The compact commission shall promulgate reasonable rules in order to
6 effectively and efficiently implement and administer the purposes and provisions of the
7 compact. A rule shall be invalid and have no force or effect only if a court of competent
8 jurisdiction holds that the rule is invalid because the compact commission exercised its
9 rulemaking authority in a manner that is beyond the scope and purposes of the
10 compact, or the powers granted hereunder, or based upon another applicable standard
11 of review.
12 B. The rules of the compact commission shall have the force of law in each
13 member state, provided however that where the rules conflict with the laws or
14 regulations of a member state that relate to the scope of practice a licensed athletic
15 trainer is permitted to undertake in that state and the circumstances under which they
16 may do so, as held by a court of competent jurisdiction, the rules of the compact
17 commission shall be ineffective in that state to the extent of the conflict.
18 C. The compact commission shall exercise its rulemaking powers pursuant to
19 the criteria set forth in this section and the rules adopted thereunder. Rules of this
20 compact shall become binding on the day following adoption or as of the date specified
21 in the rule or amendment, whichever is later.
22 D. If a majority of the legislatures of the member states rejects a rule or
23 portion of a rule, by enactment of a statute or resolution in the same manner used to
24 adopt the compact within four (4) years of the date of adoption of the rule, then such
25 rule shall have no further force and effect in any member state.
26 E. Rules shall be adopted at a regular or special meeting of the compact
27 commission.
Page 23 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 F. Prior to adoption of a proposed rule, the compact commission shall hold a
2 public hearing and allow persons to provide oral and written comments, data, facts,
3 opinions, and arguments. At least thirty (30) days in advance of the public hearing on
4 the proposed rule, the compact commission shall provide a notice of proposed
5 rulemaking:
6 1. On the website of the compact commission or other publicly accessible
7 platform;
8 2. To persons who have requested notice of the compact commission’s notices
9 of proposed rulemaking; and
10 3. In such other way(s) as the compact commission may by rule specify.
11 G. The notice of proposed rulemaking shall include:
12 1. The time, date, and location of the public hearing at which the compact
13 commission will hear public comments on the proposed rule and, if different, the time,
14 date, and location of the meeting where the compact commission will consider and vote
15 on the proposed rule;
16 2. If the hearing is held via telecommunication, video conference, or other
17 electronic means, the compact commission shall include the mechanism for access to
18 the hearing in the notice of proposed rulemaking;
19 3. The text of the proposed rule and the reason therefor;
20 4. A request for comments on the proposed rule from any interested person;
21 and
22 5. The manner in which interested persons may submit written comments.
23 H. All hearings will be recorded. A copy of the recording and all written
24 comments and documents received by the compact commission in response to the
25 proposed rule shall be available to the public.
26 I. Nothing in this section shall be construed as requiring a separate hearing
27 on each rule. Rules may be grouped for the convenience of the compact commission at
Page 24 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 hearings required by this section.
2 J. The compact commission shall, by majority vote of all members, take final
3 action on the proposed rule based on the rulemaking record and the full text of the
4 rule.
5 1. The compact commission may adopt changes to the proposed rule provided
6 the changes do not enlarge the original purpose of the proposed rule.
7 2. The compact commission shall provide an explanation of the reasons for
8 substantive changes made to the proposed rule as well as reasons for substantive
9 changes not made that were recommended by commenters.
10 3. The compact commission shall determine a reasonable effective date for the
11 rule. Except for an emergency as provided in this section, the effective date of the rule
12 shall be no sooner than 30 days after issuing the notice that it adopted or amended the
13 rule.
14 K. Upon determination that an emergency exists, the compact commission may
15 consider and adopt an emergency rule with 24 hours’ notice, with opportunity to
16 comment, provided that the usual rulemaking procedures provided in the compact and
17 in this section shall be retroactively applied to the rule as soon as reasonably possible,
18 in no event later than ninety (90) days after the effective date of the rule. For the
19 purposes of this provision, an emergency rule is one that must be adopted immediately
20 in order to:
21 1. Meet an imminent threat to public health, safety, or welfare;
22 2. Prevent a loss of compact commission or member state funds;
23 3. Meet a deadline for the promulgation of a rule that is established by federal
24 law or rule; or
25 4. Protect public health and safety.
26 L. The compact commission or an authorized committee of the compact
27 commission may direct revisions to a previously adopted rule for purposes of correcting
Page 25 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 typographical errors, errors in format, errors in consistency, or grammatical errors.
2 Public notice of any revisions shall be posted on the website of the compact
3 commission. The revision shall be subject to challenge by any person for a period of
4 thirty (30) days after posting. The revision may be challenged only on grounds that the
5 revision results in a material change to a rule. A challenge shall be made in writing
6 and delivered to the compact commission prior to the end of the notice period. If no
7 challenge is made, the revision will take effect without further action. If the revision is
8 challenged, the revision may not take effect without the approval of the compact
9 commission.
10 M. No member state’s rulemaking requirements shall apply under this
11 compact.
12 SECTION 11. OVERSIGHT, DISPUTE RESOLUTION, AND
13 ENFORCEMENT
14 A. Oversight:
15 1. The executive and judicial branches of state government in each member
16 state shall enforce this compact and take all actions necessary and appropriate to
17 implement the compact.
18 2. Except as otherwise provided in this compact, venue is proper and judicial
19 proceedings by or against the compact commission shall be brought solely and
20 exclusively in a court of competent jurisdiction where the principal office of the
21 compact commission is located. The compact commission may waive venue and
22 jurisdictional defenses to the extent it adopts or consents to participate in alternative
23 dispute resolution proceedings. Nothing herein shall affect or limit the selection or
24 propriety of venue in any action against a licensee for professional malpractice,
25 misconduct or any such similar matter.
26 3. The compact commission shall be entitled to receive service of process in
27 any proceeding regarding the enforcement or interpretation of the compact and shall
Page 26 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 have standing to intervene in such a proceeding for all purposes. Failure to provide the
2 compact commission service of process shall render a judgment or order void as to the
3 compact commission, this compact, or promulgated rules.
4 B. Default, Technical Assistance, and Termination:
5 1. If the compact commission determines that a member state has defaulted in
6 the performance of its obligations or responsibilities under this compact or the
7 promulgated rules, the commission shall provide written notice to the defaulting state.
8 The notice of default shall describe the default, the proposed means of curing the
9 default, and any other action that the compact commission may take, and shall offer
10 training and specific technical assistance regarding the default.
11 2. The compact commission shall provide a copy of the notice of default to the
12 other member states.
13 C. If a state in default fails to cure the default, the defaulting state may be
14 terminated from the compact upon an affirmative vote of a majority of the
15 commissioners of the member states, and all rights, privileges and benefits conferred
16 on that state by this compact may be terminated on the effective date of termination. A
17 cure of the default does not relieve the offending state of obligations or liabilities
18 incurred during the period of default.
19 D. Termination of membership in the compact shall be imposed only after all
20 other means of securing compliance have been exhausted. Notice of intent to suspend
21 or terminate shall be given by the compact commission to the governor, the majority
22 and minority leaders of the defaulting state’s legislature, the defaulting state’s
23 licensing authority and each of the member states’ licensing authority.
24 E. A state that has been terminated is responsible for all assessments,
25 obligations, and liabilities incurred through the effective date of termination, including
26 obligations that extend beyond the effective date of termination.
27 F. Upon the termination of a state’s membership from this compact, that state
Page 27 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 shall immediately provide notice to all licensees within that state of such termination.
2 The terminated state shall continue to recognize all licenses and compact privileges
3 granted pursuant to this compact for a minimum of 180 days after the date of said
4 notice of termination.
5 G. The compact commission shall not bear any costs related to a state that is
6 found to be in default or that has been terminated from the compact, unless agreed
7 upon in writing between the compact commission and the defaulting state.
8 H. The defaulting state may appeal the action of the compact commission by
9 petitioning the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia or the federal district
10 where the compact commission has its principal offices. The prevailing party shall be
11 awarded all costs of such litigation, including reasonable attorney’s fees.
12 I. Dispute Resolution:
13 1. Upon request by a member state, the compact commission shall attempt to
14 resolve disputes related to the compact that arise among member states and between
15 member and non-member states.
16 2. The compact commission shall promulgate a rule providing for both
17 mediation and binding dispute resolution for disputes as appropriate.
18 J. Enforcement:
19 1. By two-thirds majority (2/3) vote, the compact commission may initiate legal
20 action against a member state in default in the United States District Court for the
21 District of Columbia or the federal district where the compact commission has its
22 principal offices to enforce compliance with the provisions of the compact and its
23 promulgated rules. The relief sought may include both injunctive relief and damages.
24 In the event judicial enforcement is necessary, the prevailing party shall be awarded all
25 costs of such litigation, including reasonable attorney’s fees. The remedies herein shall
26 not be the exclusive remedies of the compact commission. The compact commission
27 may pursue any other remedies available under federal or the defaulting member
Page 28 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 state’s law.
2 2. A member state may initiate legal action against the compact commission in
3 the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia or the federal district where the
4 compact commission has its principal offices to enforce compliance with the provisions
5 of the compact and its promulgated rules. The relief sought may include both
6 injunctive relief and damages. In the event judicial enforcement is necessary, the
7 prevailing party shall be awarded all costs of such litigation, including reasonable
8 attorney’s fees.
9 3. No person other than a member state shall enforce this compact against the
10 compact commission.
11 SECTION 12. EFFECTIVE DATE, WITHDRAWAL, AND AMENDMENT
12 A. The compact shall come into effect on the date on which the compact statute
13 is enacted into law in the seventh member state.
14 1. On or after the effective date of the compact, the compact commission shall
15 convene and review the enactment of each of the first seven member states ("charter
16 member states") to determine if the statute enacted and made effective by each such
17 charter member state is materially different than the model compact statute.
18 a. A charter member state whose enactment is found to be materially different
19 from the model compact language shall be entitled to the default process set forth in
20 Section 11.
21 b. If any member state is later found to be in default, or is terminated or
22 withdraws from the compact, the compact commission shall remain in existence and
23 the compact shall remain in effect even if the number of member states should be less
24 than seven.
25 2. Member states enacting the compact subsequent to the seven initial charter
26 member states shall be subject to the process set forth in this section to determine if
27 their enactments are materially different from the model compact statute and whether
Page 29 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 they qualify for participation in the compact.
2 3. All actions taken for the benefit of the compact commission or in
3 furtherance of the purposes of the administration of the compact prior to the effective
4 date of the compact or the compact commission coming into existence shall be
5 considered to be actions of the compact commission unless specifically repudiated by
6 the compact commission.
7 4. Any state that joins the compact subsequent to the compact commission’s
8 initial adoption of the rules and bylaws shall be subject to the rules and bylaws as they
9 exist on the date on which the compact becomes law in that state. Any rule that has
10 been previously adopted by the compact commission shall have the full force and effect
11 of law on the day the compact becomes law in that state.
12 B. Any member state may withdraw from this compact by enacting a statute
13 repealing the same.
14 1. A member state’s withdrawal shall not take effect until 180 days after
15 enactment of the repealing statute.
16 2. Withdrawal shall not affect the continuing requirement of the withdrawing
17 state’s licensing authority to comply with the investigative and adverse action reporting
18 requirements of this compact prior to the effective date of withdrawal.
19 3. Upon the enactment of a statute withdrawing from this compact, a state
20 shall immediately provide notice of such withdrawal to all licensees and privilege
21 holders within that state. Notwithstanding any subsequent statutory enactment to the
22 contrary, such withdrawing state shall continue to recognize all compact privileges
23 granted pursuant to this compact for a minimum of 180 days after the date of such
24 notice of withdrawal.
25 4. Nothing contained in this compact shall be construed to invalidate or
26 prevent any licensure agreement or other cooperative arrangement between a member
27 state and a non-member state that does not conflict with the provisions of this compact.
Page 30 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 5. This compact may be amended by the member states. No amendment to this
2 compact shall become effective and binding upon any member state until it is enacted
3 into the laws of all member states.
4 SECTION 13. CONSTRUCTION AND SEVERABILITY
5 A. This compact and the compact commission’s rulemaking authority shall be
6 liberally construed so as to effectuate the purposes, and the implementation and
7 administration of the compact. Provisions of the compact expressly authorizing or
8 requiring the promulgation of rules shall not be construed to limit the compact
9 commission’s rulemaking authority solely for those purposes.
10 B. The provisions of this compact shall be severable and if any phrase, clause,
11 sentence or provision of this compact is held by a court of competent jurisdiction to be
12 contrary to the constitution of any member state, a state seeking participation in the
13 compact, or of the United States, or the applicability thereof to any government,
14 agency, person or circumstance is held to be unconstitutional by a court of competent
15 jurisdiction, the validity of the remainder of this compact and the applicability thereof
16 to any other government, agency, person or circumstance shall not be affected thereby.
17 C. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the compact commission may deny a state’s
18 participation in the compact or terminate a member state’s participation in the compact
19 if it determines that a constitutional requirement of a member state is a material
20 departure from the compact. Otherwise, if this compact shall be held to be contrary to
21 the constitution of any member state, the compact shall remain in full force and effect
22 as to the remaining member states and in full force and effect as to the member state
23 affected as to all severable matters.
24 SECTION 14. CONSISTENT EFFECT AND CONFLICT WITH OTHER
25 STATE LAWS
26 A. Nothing herein shall prevent or inhibit the enforcement of any other law of
27 a member state that is not inconsistent with the compact.
Page 31 of 32
XXXX 2/10/2026 12:57 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1802
1 B. Any laws, statutes, regulations, or other legal requirements in a member
2 state in conflict with the compact are superseded to the extent of the conflict.
3 C. All permissible agreements between the compact commission and the
4 member states are binding in accordance with their terms.
